<h2>Overview</h2>
<p>The <code>open</code> attribute is a boolean attribute that controls the visibility of expandable content. It applies to two elements:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong><a href="/docs/elements/native/details/"><code>&lt;details&gt;</code></a></strong> — controls whether the disclosure widget is expanded or collapsed</li>
  <li><strong><a href="/docs/elements/native/dialog/"><code>&lt;dialog&gt;</code></a></strong> — controls whether the dialog is visible (non-modal)</li>
</ul>
<p>When <code>open</code> is present, the content is shown. When absent, it is hidden.</p>

<h2>Details Element</h2>
<p>On <code>&lt;details&gt;</code>, the <code>open</code> attribute determines whether the content below the <code>&lt;summary&gt;</code> is visible. Users can toggle it by clicking the summary. Add <code>open</code> in markup to have the section expanded on page load.</p>

<code-block language="html" label="Details with open">{{ detailsExample | escape }}</code-block>

<h2>Exclusive Accordions with name</h2>
<p>The <code>name</code> attribute on <code>&lt;details&gt;</code> creates an exclusive accordion group. When multiple <code>&lt;details&gt;</code> elements share the same <code>name</code>, opening one automatically closes the others — no JavaScript required.</p>

<code-block language="html" label="Accordion group">{{ accordionExample | escape }}</code-block>

<h2>Dialog Element</h2>
<p>On <code>&lt;dialog&gt;</code>, the <code>open</code> attribute makes the dialog visible as a non-modal overlay. However, for modal dialogs you should use <code>showModal()</code> instead, which adds the <code>open</code> attribute automatically and also provides backdrop, focus trapping, and Escape-to-close behavior.</p>

<code-block language="html" label="Dialog open vs showModal">{{ dialogExample | escape }}</code-block>

