<h2>Accessibility</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Screen readers announce <code>&lt;details&gt;</code> as a disclosure widget with its expanded/collapsed state.</li>
  <li>The <code>&lt;summary&gt;</code> element is focusable and activatable via keyboard (Enter and Space).</li>
  <li>For <code>&lt;dialog&gt;</code>, always prefer <code>showModal()</code> over the <code>open</code> attribute — it ensures proper focus management and keyboard behavior.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Limitations</h2>
<ul>
  <li>The <code>name</code> attribute for exclusive accordion groups is relatively new. Older browsers will treat each <code>&lt;details&gt;</code> independently.</li>
  <li>There is no built-in animation for <code>&lt;details&gt;</code> open/close transitions. CSS transitions on height require workarounds.</li>
  <li>Setting <code>open</code> directly on a <code>&lt;dialog&gt;</code> in markup creates a non-modal dialog with no backdrop or focus trapping, which is rarely what you want.</li>
  <li>The <code>toggle</code> event is not cancellable — you cannot prevent the state change from within the handler.</li>
</ul>

<aside>
  <h3>VB Enhancement</h3>
  <p>A future <code>data-accordion</code> attribute could add smooth open/close animations to <code>&lt;details&gt;</code> elements using the Web Animations API, and polyfill <code>name</code>-based exclusivity for browsers that do not yet support it.</p>
</aside>

